What is private offline is both private and online
Private.
According to the dictionary issued by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that has a personal character or a "private life area that everyone has the right to protect against any interference".
What is privacy for a person under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers that he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet issues that he would certainly not tell anyone during regular communication?
Journalists from elPeriodico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years old who are frequent internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" in personal terms and as "user name and password" when it was a social network.
"My biggest secret would not be published," Jorge says in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secretive, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing at the FB.
I'm talking to my friends there, too.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine, or a photo that would make fun of someone," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 of his friends on the FB and his nine Twitter fans.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up a Twitter account so I could express my views and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone's gonna answer, I'm just putting them in there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from a stranger.
He wouldn't even care if he was recommended by someone unknown.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid because we have something in common, such as music," she says.
According to this boy, none of them set him up, nor did he ask for an address or a phone number.
"If they insist on me or require me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading his Twitter recommendations.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
"They blackmailed friends on the social media.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he says.
According to José, the victim didn't log out of the account.
"She's only activated a private regime."
Then he explains a series of steps how to set up an account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of people known in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I'd do it if I didn't care or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to be well-oriented on social networks, they need to understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform themselves.
He states that: "Internet was created as a means of searching for information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital natives and digital immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, yet we are only learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at the age when they are not mature".
Also, to be, as far as the surroundings are concerned, discreet, at a time when what they most desire is to be liked, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way is to show children and adolescents what privacy is, to ask questions that make them think.
"Tell them not to do anything, it's not working," he adds.
Furthermore, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: Are there things you would not tell a stranger, so why are you doing this on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your photo the way you posted your friend?
Do you know what the others publish about you?
When you label people in the photos of the celebrations, did you ask them for permission?
And one more: does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they must behave in the Internet as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
"Man is out of the Internet guided by respect, morality and other principles, and it should be the same on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-degree teacher, and an educational advisor explains that it is essential for parents to read the social network rules carefully.
"If they understand every trickery, they have a good reason to talk to the children about the consequences that an online account may have.
For example, when it comes to age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
Guardia believes that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "do not speak to strangers".
